          <h2 class="details-title">Tadoba-Andhari Tiger Reserve: A Wildlife Haven in Maharashtra</h2>
          <p>
            Nestled in the heart of Maharashtra’s Chandrapur district, the Tadoba-Andhari Tiger Reserve (TATR) is one of
            India’s finest wildlife sanctuaries. Known as the “Jewel of Vidarbha,” it is Maharashtra’s oldest and
            largest national park. The reserve is a treasure trove of biodiversity, offering an unforgettable experience
            for nature enthusiasts and wildlife photographers.
          </p>
          <h5>A Brief History</h5>
          <p>
            The Tadoba-Andhari Tiger Reserve derives its name from two sources: Tadoba, the local deity worshipped by
            tribes, and Andhari, a river that meanders through the forest. Established in 1955 as a national park and
            later merged with the Andhari Wildlife Sanctuary in 1995, the reserve now spans over 1,727 square kilometers
            of protected area.
          </p>
          <h5>Wildlife at Tadoba</h5>
          <p>TATR is renowned for its significant population of Royal Bengal Tigers, making it one of the best places in
            India for tiger sightings. In addition to tigers, the reserve is home to:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Leopards, sloth bears, Indian gaur (bison), and wild dogs.</li>
            <li>Herbivores like spotted deer, sambar, nilgai, and four-horned antelopes.</li>
            <li>Reptiles, including crocodiles, monitor lizards, and various snake species.</li>
            <li>Over <strong>195 species of birds</strong>, such as crested serpent eagles, grey-headed fish eagles, and
              paradise flycatchers.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>The park’s diverse ecosystem ensures that every safari is filled with thrilling encounters.</p>
          <h5>Flora and Landscapes</h5>
          <p>Tadoba’s terrain is a mix of dense forests, grasslands, and water bodies. The vegetation is primarily dry
            deciduous, dominated by teak, bamboo, and crocodile bark trees. Seasonal flowers and grasses bloom, creating
            a vibrant landscape during the monsoon and post-monsoon seasons. The Tadoba Lake and the Andhari River act
            as lifelines, supporting the wildlife and enhancing the reserve’s scenic beauty.</p>
          <h5>Activities and Attractions</h5>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Jungle Safaris</strong>: The reserve offers morning and evening safaris, allowing visitors to explore the core
              and buffer zones. These guided tours maximize chances of spotting tigers and other wildlife.
            <br>
            <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;" src="https://mytadoba.mahaforest.gov.in/frontAssets/assets/images/blog/image-tiger-2.jpg">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Photography</strong>: Tadoba’s picturesque landscapes and rich biodiversity make it a paradise for photographers.
              <br>
